ased on strong primary research - including the previously un-consulted journals and records produced by the many journalistic representative organisations that came and went over the decades - and written in an accessible and engaging style, The Fourth Estate will appeal to anyone interested in journalism, history, the media and the development of Ireland as a modern nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJournalismzIrelandxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aBroadcasting.  aCatholic Church.  aHistory.  aInvestigative journalism.  aIreland.  aJournalism.  aNewspapers.  aPeriodicals.  aPolitics.  aSocial change.1 aO’Brien, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610842540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526108425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526108425/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles